<h2>What we mean by charitable work</h2>
<p><strong>Charitable work</strong> is the set of <strong>structured projects, campaigns and commitments</strong> through which the Brotherhood organises its social outreach over time. If assistance work responds to day-to-day needs, charitable work gives that same spirit <strong>continuity, internal visibility and planning</strong>: it sets priorities for the cofrade year, mobilises resources in a Gospel-driven way and prevents charity from shrinking to isolated gestures without memory or accountability.</p>
<h2>Projects and campaigns</h2>
<p>Typical initiatives may include <strong>seasonal appeals</strong> (food drives, school supplies or hygiene items), <strong>one-off partnerships</strong> with parish Caritas, hospitals or care homes, support for vulnerable families agreed with the <strong>Charity board</strong>, and solidarity events tied to the liturgical year or the penitential procession. Each proposal is assessed for <strong>feasibility, impact and fit</strong> with the corporation’s statutory aims, with approval from the competent bodies.</p>
<h2>Resources and transparency</h2>
<p>This work is funded by <strong>designated donations</strong>, budget lines approved by the Governing Board or the General Assembly, and the generosity of members and devotees who trust sound stewardship. The Brotherhood seeks <strong>transparency</strong> in how funds are used: those in charge report regularly to governance and keep records and receipts that support orderly administration, in line with <strong>applicable law</strong> and accountability to the parish community.</p>
<h2>Coordination and synergy</h2>
<p>Charitable work does not compete with <strong>assistance work</strong> or duplicate what other neighbourhood bodies already do: it is coordinated with the Charity board, volunteers and the parish priest so that each initiative has a <strong>clear owner, timetable and follow-up</strong>. Overlaps are avoided, partnerships with the <strong>Diocese</strong> or the local council are strengthened where appropriate, and the Brotherhood speaks with one voice to those who receive help.</p>
<h2>Participation and the future</h2>
